-- Article 43: Dysphagia and Oesophageal Diseases
-- Surgery 2 CME Content

-- Insert sections

ESOPHAGEAL DYSPHAGIA - MECHANICAL: Benign stricture (peptic, caustic, post-radiation), malignant stricture (esophageal or gastric cardia cancer), esophageal web (Plummer-Vinson/Patterson-Kelly syndrome with iron deficiency), Schatzki ring (mucosal ring at GE junction), extrinsic compression.

ESOPHAGEAL DYSPHAGIA - MOTILITY: Achalasia, diffuse esophageal spasm, nutcracker esophagus, scleroderma. Dysphagia to both solids and liquids. Motility disorders diagnosed by esophageal manometry.

INVESTIGATIONS: Barium swallow (first-line for oropharyngeal, pharyngeal pouch, motility disorders). Upper GI endoscopy (visualization, biopsy, therapeutic). CT scan (staging for malignancy). Esophageal manometry (motility disorders). pH studies (GERD assessment).'),
('d0000043-0000-0000-0000-000000000043'::uuid, 'content', 3, 'Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Complications', 'GERD: Reflux of gastric contents causing symptoms or complications. Heartburn, regurgitation, waterbrash. Risk factors: obesity, hiatal hernia, pregnancy, smoking, certain foods.

COMPLICATIONS: Esophagitis (Los Angeles classification A-D), peptic stricture, Barrett esophagus (intestinal metaplasia - premalignant), adenocarcinoma.

BARRETT ESOPHAGUS: Columnar metaplasia replacing squamous epithelium. Risk of adenocarcinoma 0.5% per year. Surveillance endoscopy with quadrantic biopsies. Dysplasia management: low-grade - surveillance or endoscopic therapy; high-grade - endoscopic resection/ablation.

HIATAL HERNIA: Type I (sliding) - 95%, GE junction slides into chest. Type II (paraesophageal) - GE junction in normal position, fundus herniates. Type III (mixed) - both components. Type IV - other organs (colon, spleen) herniate. Paraesophageal hernias risk strangulation.

MANAGEMENT: Lifestyle modifications (weight loss, elevate head of bed, avoid triggers). PPIs (first-line medical). Surgery (Nissen fundoplication - laparoscopic) for refractory GERD, large hiatal hernia, complications. Anti-reflux procedures: complete (Nissen 360) or partial (Toupet 270 posterior, Dor 180 anterior).'),
('d0000043-0000-0000-0000-000000000043'::uuid, 'content', 4, 'Achalasia and Other Motility Disorders', 'ACHALASIA: Failure of LES relaxation due to degeneration of myenteric plexus ganglion cells. Progressive dysphagia to solids AND liquids, regurgitation of undigested food, weight loss, chest pain. Bird beak appearance on barium swallow. Absent peristalsis and incomplete LES relaxation on manometry.

TREATMENT: Pneumatic (balloon) dilation (70-80% effective), Heller myotomy (laparoscopic, combined with partial fundoplication), peroral endoscopic myotomy (POEM), botulinum toxin injection (temporary). Surgery most durable long-term.

DIFFUSE ESOPHAGEAL SPASM: Intermittent dysphagia and chest pain. Corkscrew esophagus on barium swallow. Simultaneous non-peristaltic contractions on manometry. Treat with calcium channel blockers, nitrates.

PHARYNGEAL POUCH (Zenker Diverticulum): Pulsion diverticulum through Killian dehiscence (between thyropharyngeal and cricopharyngeal parts of inferior constrictor). Presents with dysphagia, regurgitation of undigested food, halitosis, aspiration, neck swelling (gurgling). Treatment: endoscopic stapling or open surgery (diverticulectomy or diverticulopexy with cricopharyngeal myotomy).

ESOPHAGEAL PERFORATION: Boerhaave syndrome (spontaneous perforation after vomiting). Iatrogenic (endoscopy most common cause). Presents with chest pain, surgical emphysema, fever. Mackler triad: vomiting, chest pain, subcutaneous emphysema. CXR shows pneumomediastinum. CT with oral contrast confirms. Management: NPO, IV antibiotics, drainage. Small contained perforations may be managed conservatively or with stent. Surgical repair for larger perforations.'),
('d0000043-0000-0000-0000-000000000043'::uuid, 'clinical_pearls', 5, 'Clinical Pearls', 'Progressive dysphagia to solids suggests mechanical obstruction; solids and liquids from onset suggests motility disorder. Bird beak on barium swallow is achalasia. Corkscrew esophagus is diffuse esophageal spasm. Barrett esophagus is premalignant - requires surveillance. Pharyngeal pouch causes regurgitation of undigested food and halitosis. Boerhaave syndrome: spontaneous esophageal perforation after vomiting.'),
('d0000043-0000-0000-0000-000000000043'::uuid, 'key_points', 6, 'Key Points Summary', 'Dysphagia requires investigation to exclude malignancy. Oropharyngeal dysphagia: difficulty initiating swallow. Esophageal dysphagia: food sticks after swallowing. GERD complications: stricture, Barrett, adenocarcinoma. Barrett esophagus: intestinal metaplasia, 0.5% annual cancer risk. Achalasia: LES fails to relax, bird beak on barium. Treatment: Heller myotomy or balloon dilation. Esophageal perforation (Boerhaave): emergency, Mackler triad.');

